trong>Meet Unit21</strong></h3><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Over those next three weeks, Trisha=
 and Clarence did a lot:&nbsp;</p><ul style=3D"margin: 1em 0;"><li style=3D=
"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"co=
lor: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">Figured out w=
hat an &#8220;RFP&#8221; is</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.=
5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">Incorporated Unit21, Inc.</p></li><li st=
yle=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">Built a=
 prototype</p></li></ul><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Then, they showed up to eBay&#8217;s HQ in=
 San Jose. They brought along one of Kothari&#8217;s former Affirm colleagu=
es to make the team look a little bigger.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a=
1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">The three of th=
em presented the prototype that they&#8217;d built over the last 20 days, w=
ent home, and then heard from eBay&#8230; that they were the front-runner o=
ut of four chosen finalists. Of the other three, the smallest was a $3 bill=
ion company. Unit21 was three weeks old and worth $0 on paper.&nbsp;</p><p =
style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1e=
m 0;">How was three-week-old Unit21 even a contender?&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"=
color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">In =
the past, there were two ways that companies built their AML/fraud models:&=
nbsp;</p><ol style=3D"margin: 1em 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px =
7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">Built something fully custom in-house =
using internal engineering teams.&nbsp;</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px=
 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">Bought something off the she=
lf from a vendor and spent half a million or so dollars to customize it.&nb=
sp;</p></li></ol><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">In the latter case, companies would buy a product=
, integrate it into their system, tweak the inputs, and then trust a black =
box to spit out when a transaction was suspicious. They often erred on the =
side of being too cautious, sending humans a rash of false positives to sif=
t through.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Every AML product with which Unit21 competes o=
ffers transaction monitoring that looks at a few things like who the paymen=
t is to and from, what industry they&#8217;re in, what country the payment =
is going to, and the volume and value of transactions. They look at the dat=
a and assign a risk score, and higher-risk transactions are sent to humans =
for review.&nbsp;</p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" style=
